Package com.googlecode.cqengine

Class ObjectLockingIndexedCollection<O>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.googlecode.cqengine.ConcurrentIndexedCollection<O>
      • com.googlecode.cqengine.ObjectLockingIndexedCollection<O>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    QueryEngine<O>, IndexedCollection<O>, Iterable<O>, Collection<O>, Set<O>
    public class ObjectLockingIndexedCollection<O>
extends ConcurrentIndexedCollection<O>
    Extends ConcurrentIndexedCollection with some specialized locking for applications in which multiple threads might try to add or remove the same object to/from an indexed collection concurrently. In this context the same object refers to either the same object instance, OR two object instances having the same hash code and being equal according to their ConcurrentIndexedCollection.equals(Object) methods.

    The ConcurrentIndexedCollection superclass is thread-safe in cases where the application will add/remove different objects concurrently. This implementation adds safeguards around adding/removing the same object concurrently, with some additional overhead.

    Reading threads are never blocked; reads remain lock-free as in the superclass.

    This class is currently implemented with a striped lock (although not the Guava implementation). As such, the hash code of an object is not assigned a unique lock, but there is instead a many-to-fewer association between hash codes and locks. Some different objects will therefore contend for the same lock. The number of stripes (locks) is configurable, allowing this ratio and likelihood of contention to be controlled, trading memory overhead of a large number of locks, against likelihood of contention. Two or more modifications for the same object, will always block each other. Two or more modifications for different objects will usually not block each other, but occasionally might.

    Although this class is currently implemented with a striped lock, this might be replaced with a stamped lock. Applications should not rely on the locking behaviour of this class, except to guard against the concurrent access scenario stated above.

    Author:
    Niall Gallagher
